english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Seeing Off Zhou, a Scholar of the National Academy
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long read the poems of Yifu and Hanlu, and I have marveled at the supreme virtue of the Zhou dynasty. One says, "King Wen lived long—did he not inspire all people?" Another says, "Harmonious noble ones—did they not inspire all people?" Indeed, the virtue of Heaven and Earth is lofty and profound, enduring through endless ages; thus their generation of all things knows no limit. The virtue of the sage is also lofty and profound, enduring through endless ages; thus his inspiration of all people likewise knows no limit. The virtue of King Wen was like that of Heaven and Earth itself. Harmony is the virtue of loftiness and depth; longevity is the effect of enduring ages. Through such virtue comes such achievement. When accumulation is long and penetration runs deep, when a worthy person is born, they already possess the clarity and purity of vital force, already embody the beauty and brilliance of teaching, and thus achieve both fame and excellence. This is why the poets never tired of singing its praises in countless verses.

    Consider now our Great Ancestor, the High Emperor. His lofty and profound virtue matched Heaven and Earth. He ruled ten thousand lands for thirty years and more. The three luminaries and five peaks did not separate; the customs became pure and wholesome; the flourishing of our people reached its peak. The Way of the teacher was established; civilization and enlightenment illuminated all. The work of inspiring and cultivating the people was perfected. All who held position in the hundred offices were accomplished in virtue and abundant in talent. All who studied in the National Academy possessed understanding of substance and mastery of application. The achievement of longevity and inspiring people was truly not inferior to King Wen.

    Now our Sage Emperor inherits the glorious deeds of his ancestor. His deep benevolence and generous grace soak the four seas. He casts his gaze particularly upon our eastern land, his care for us most diligent. Rewards and honors arrive in succession. For the sake of military preparedness, he sent envoys to purchase horses, showing he regards us as one family.

    At this time, the Minister of Steeds, Lord Zhu, and the Director of the Military Bureau, Lord Duanmu, received this commission. Ten scholars of the National Academy, the officials accompanying them, came one after another, deep as pools, brilliant as flowers, their refined writings shining together like jade and precious stones in mutual radiance. By the elegance of these two nobles and the excellence of these ten scholars, one may perceive the flourishing of talent in this age. The last to arrive was Lord Zhou Gui—youngest in years yet most mature in learning, most dignified in conduct, most respectful in ceremony. The two nobles cherished him especially, and our eastern people held him in high regard.

    As he departed with the two nobles, the literary gentlemen presented him with poems. I too spoke, saying: "Heaven and Earth generate ten thousand things, yet the ten thousand things reveal the transformations of Heaven and Earth. The sage cultivates talented people, yet talented people also assist in the virtue of the sage. These two are eternally interdependent in their function. Thus the many scholars of ancient Zhou arose from King Wen's transformative influence, fulfilling their talents, while King Wen in turn depended upon these scholars' aid to bring peace to his realm. Is it not true what was said: 'Many able scholars secure King Wen's peace'? The many scholars of today, having received the enduring grace of our High Emperor and the nurturing benevolence of our Sage Emperor, have achieved their virtue. Through promotion and declaration, they shine in the court; through counsel and deliberation, they labor abroad. They race to repel invaders and earn merit through strategy, enabling our age to achieve such splendor of governance as to surpass even the three ancient dynasties, leaving eternal glory for endless generations. Each finds those suited to these tasks. Lord Zhou, in company with the two nobles, moves through these affairs—different in form yet identical in function. To leave their names honored through the ages will surely begin from this moment."

    I have long admired the virtue of King Wen, and now I am blessed to witness its equal in my own time. Thus I write this preface with joy.
  footnotes:
    - Yifu and Hanlu are titles of odes from the Book of Odes (Shijing) praising the virtue of King Wen of the Zhou dynasty.
    - The three luminaries refer to the sun, moon, and stars; the five peaks to the sacred mountains—metaphorical expressions for universal harmony and order.
    - The National Academy (Guozijian) was the state educational institution during the early Ming period.
    - This preface was likely written during the Joseon period when Ming envoys, including the mentioned Lord Zhou, visited Korea.
